threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a trojan/dropper that implements persistence and payload execution. It uses sub_404480 to copy itself into the user profile directory as 'Windows-KB275122-x86.exe' and creates a registry entry under 'Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run' named 'Windows Update' to ensure it runs on startup. The binary also searches for ZIP and LNK files, drops malicious RTF documents into the Temp directory (e.g., 'Rar0tmpExtra%d.rtf'), and executes them using ShellExecuteW. Furthermore, it employs a long Sleep call (approx. 6 minutes) as a standard anti-sandbox evasion technique. Notable IOCs include the deceptive registry value name and the specific 'KB' themed executable filename.
